# Finalizer no longer called in .NET Core 2.0 after GC.Collect / GC.WaitForPendingFinalizers

As of **.NET Core 2.0**, an object's finalizer **is no longer called** when calling `GC.Collect` and `GC.WaitForPendingFinalizers`.

# General

To be clear: the following code works as advertised in .NET Framework 4.7 and earlier; .NET Core 1.1 and earlier; but not in .NET Core 2.0:

```csharp
[TestClass]
public class GarbageCollectionTest
{
    [TestMethod]
    [Description("Asserts that an un-rooted object's finalizer will be called.")]
    public void GarbageCollectionTest01()
    {
        // Instantiate a spy to record that the Foo finalizer is called.
        var spy = new Spy();

        // Instantiate a new Foo.
        var foo = new Foo(spy);

        // Unroot foo.
        foo = null;

        // Force a collection.
        GC.Collect(0, GCCollectionMode.Forced, blocking: true);

        // Wait for all finalizers to have executed.
        GC.WaitForPendingFinalizers();

        // Assert that Foo's finalizer is called.
        // WARNING: This assertion fails in .NET Core 2.0, but works in .NET Core 1.1 and .NET Framework 4.7 and before.
        Assert.IsTrue(spy.FinalizerIsCalled);
    }

    private class Spy
    {
        public bool FinalizerIsCalled { get; set; }
    }

    private class Foo
    {
        ~Foo()
        {
            spy.FinalizerIsCalled = true;
        }

        public Foo(Spy spy)
        {
            this.spy = spy;
        }

        private readonly Spy spy;
    }
}
```

Unit test output:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/938393/33224269-df6ee77a-d167-11e7-857c-2fdfec794574.png)

To demonstrate the issue, I created a unit test project for the following frameworks which all share the same .cs file:

- .NET Framework 4.7 [passing]
- .NET Core 1.0 [passing]
- .NET Core 1.1 [passing]
- .NET Core 2.0 *[failing]*

[GarbageCollectionTests.zip](https://github.com/dotnet/core/files/1502553/GarbageCollectionTests.zip)

```
import com.microsoft.z3.BoolExpr;
import com.microsoft.z3.Context;
import com.microsoft.z3.EnumSort;
import com.microsoft.z3.Expr;
import com.microsoft.z3.Solver;
import com.microsoft.z3.Status;
import com.microsoft.z3.Symbol;
import java.util.HashMap;

public class AdvSMT {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        HashMap<String, String> cfg = new HashMap<>();
        cfg.put("model", "true");
        Context ctx = new Context(cfg);
        Solver z3 = ctx.mkSolver(); 
        Symbol name0 = ctx.mkSymbol("Enum0");
        EnumSort Enum0 = ctx.mkEnumSort(name0, ctx.mkSymbol("In_Air"),
                ctx.mkSymbol("On_Ground"), ctx.mkSymbol("None"));
        Symbol name1 = ctx.mkSymbol("Enum1"); 
        EnumSort Enum1 = ctx.mkEnumSort(name1, ctx.mkSymbol("True"), 
                ctx.mkSymbol("False"), ctx.mkSymbol("None")); 
        Expr var_0 = ctx.mkConst("var_0", Enum0);
        Expr var_1 = ctx.mkConst("var_1", Enum1); 
        BoolExpr assertion_0 = ctx.mkEq(var_0, Enum0.getConst(2));
        BoolExpr assertion_1 = ctx.mkEq(var_1, Enum1.getConst(2));
        z3.add(assertion_0);
        z3.add(assertion_1);

        // print out 
        if(z3.check()==Status.SATISFIABLE){
            System.out.println(z3.toString());
        }
    }
}
```
The code above will print out the following SMT formulas:

(declare-datatypes () ((Enum0 (In_Air) (On_Ground) (None))))
(declare-datatypes () ((Enum1 (True) (False) (None))))
(declare-fun var_0 () Enum0)
(declare-fun var_1 () Enum1)
(assert (= var_0 None))
(assert (= var_1 None))
However, those formulas will not be accepted by Z3 since the last two lines should be printed out as:

(assert (= var_0 (as None Enum0)))
(assert (= var_1 (as None Enum1)))
Is this a bug in Z3 API?

Hi, i tested the recent commit that allows bindings of void* types and noticed that returning a nullptr causes a runtime error (while returning non-null pointer works fine). Please see example code that trigger this below.

Thanks,

```c++
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <iostream>

void * foo_null_0() { return nullptr; }
void * foo_null_1() { return (void*)1234; }
void foo_null(void *p) { std::cout << p << std::endl; }

namespace py = pybind11;

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(example) {
    py::module m("example", "pybind11 example plugin");

	m.def("foo_null_0", &foo_null_0, "doc"); // invoking this in python yied: RuntimeError: Could not allocate capsule object!
	m.def("foo_null_1", &foo_null_1, "doc"); // invoking this works fine!
	m.def("foo_null", (void (*)(void*)) &foo_null, "doc", pybind11::arg(""));

    return m.ptr();
}
```

Hi, I noticed that using PYBIND11_OVERLOAD macro with somewhat complex return types might lead to strange compilation error (below). However replacing return type with its own typedef solve the issue. Please see minimal example below. Any idea what might be wrong here?

Thanks,

```c++
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

class A
{
public:
	virtual ~A() {}

	virtual std::vector<int> foo() { return std::vector<int>(); }
};

using MyVector = std::vector<int, std::allocator<int> >;

struct PyCallBack_A : public A {
	using A::A;

	// give compilation error
	//std::vector<int, std::allocator<int> > foo() override {  PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(std::vector<int, std::allocator<int> >, A, foo); }

	// works fine
	//std::vector<int, std::allocator<int> > foo() override {  PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(MyVector, A, foo); }
};

namespace py = pybind11;

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(example) {
    py::module m("example", "pybind11 example plugin");


	pybind11::class_<PyCallBack_A> cl(m, "A");
	cl.alias<A>();
	cl.def(pybind11::init<>());
	cl.def("foo", &A::foo);

    return m.ptr();
}
```



